\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. A. tomentosum} Miller, {\i Gard. Dict.} ed. 8, no. 3 (1768) ({\i Lappa tomentosa} (Miller) Lam.). Plant 50-150 cm, petioles and peduncles slightly farinose and floccose. Basal leaves up to 50 cm, broadly ovate, cordate; petioles solid. Each main branch of inflorescence corymbose, occasionally elongate. Peduncles 3-10 cm. Involucre 12-20 × 15-25 mm in fruit, usually with dense arachnoid indumentum, rarely more or less glabrous. Florets longer than involucral bracts. Achenes 5-6 mm, pale brownish; pappus 1-3·5 mm. 2n = 36.{\i  Most of Europe, but rarer in the north and west.} Au Be Bl Bu Co Cz Da Fe Ga Ge Gr He Ho Hs Hu It Ju No Po Rm Rs (N, B, C, W, K, E) Su [Br].
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 2. A. lappa} L., {\i Sp. Pl.} 816 (1753) ({\i A. majus} Bernh., {\i Lappa officinalis} All.,{\i  L. major} Gaertner). Plant 90-150 cm. Stems, petioles and peduncles pubescent to subglabrous. Each main branch of inflorescence corymbose. Basal leaves up to 50 cm, broadly ovate, cordate, usually obtuse; petioles solid. Peduncles 3-10 cm. Involucre 20-25 × 35-42 mm in fruit, globose in bud, hemispherical and widely open above in fruit, shiny golden-green, glabrous or subglabrous. Florets about as long as involucral bracts. Achenes 6-7 mm; pappus 1·3-5 mm. 2n = 36.{\i  Most of Europe except the extreme north.} All except Az ?Cr Fa Is Lu Sb ?Si.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 3. A. pubens} Bab., {\i Ann. Nat. Hist.} ser. 2, {\b 17}: 376 (1856). Plant 60-150 cm; Stems, petioles and peduncles farinose. Basal leaves up to 40 cm, broadly ovate, cordate; petioles hollow. Each main branch of inflorescence racemose; peduncles 1-4 cm, the lower longest. Involucre 20-25 × 30-35 mm in fruit, hemispherical, straw-coloured, with dense arachnoid indumentum when young, becoming subglabrous and open above in fruit. Florets about as long as involucral bracts. Achenes 5-7 mm, brownish; pappus 1·3-5 mm. {\i W., C. & S. Europe; distribution incompletely known.} Be Br Co Da Ga He Ho Hs Hu It Rm Sa.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28   Probably originated by hybridization between {\b 2} and {\b 4}.
